AVIAN INFLUENZA (68): CAMBODIA, SUSPECTED
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[While this posting has information on both human and avian influenza
issues, the human case information is not new as there are no
additional human cases having been confirmed at this time. The avian
influenza reports though are new, as a a new outbreak is suspected in
a neighboring province not having reported avian influenza in the
past. Hence, the decision has been taken to include this posting in
the avian influenza thread. - Mod.MPP]
[1]
Date: Sun 8 Apr 2007
Submitted by: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>
Source: M&C News [edited]
<http://news.monstersandcritics.com/health/news/article_1288648.php/>

Cambodia: Local media reports bird flu not yet contained
-----------------------------------------------
Two siblings of Cambodia's 7th human bird-flu fatality victim who had
initially reported symptoms were improving, but the sudden deaths of
chickens in a neighboring province raised new concerns, local media
reported on Sunday [8 Apr 2007].
The Rasmei Kampuchea newspaper [a Phnom Penh daily newspaper] quoted
local health officials as saying 2 children aged 8 and 11, believed
to be siblings of a 13-year-old girl who died of the H5N1 strain of
avian influenza [see: Avian influenza, human (68): Cambodia,
Indonesia 20070406.1161], had earlier been feared to have contracted
the disease but now appeared to be improving. The dead school girl
had tended her family's small flock of chickens in the Ponhea Kret
district of eastern Kampong Cham province, according to local residents.
The Rasmei [newspaper] quoted local officials as saying that several
were under observation in the area surrounding Phany's home and that
68 ducks and nearly 300 chickens had died in the vicinity before and
after the girl fell ill last Monday [2 Apr 2007]. Health Ministry
official Ly Sovann told Radio Free Asia that local authorities were
investigating reports of mass deaths of chickens in neighboring
Kratie Province.
The school girl was the 1st confirmed human death [in Cambodia] from
the disease since April 2006.
--
